- tradeoff: plantings can conceal criminals. but can circument this using thorns of sharp serrations

Education and cultural opportunities
- provides connection to nature
- highest engagement can occur in urban centres

Disservices
- some species provide disservices
- some plants attract unwanted insect species
- trees with large amounts of leaf litter are best avoied in pedestrian presincts
- trees with high sugar secretions are not apopriate within car parks 

Multiple benefits
- certain species are better than others in promoting multipe services
- for example, salvia offinalis and stachys byzantina provide rooftop cooling, stormwater retention, increase storage capacity, habitat provision, traps aerial pollutants and provides pollen for honey bees

What Next?
- practitioners tend to perceive plant selection as either what survives well or what looks pretty
- need to chance policymakers' perspective to only "why" plant selection is importamt, but to how "how" and "where" for effective management
- a change in philosophy from "what will survive" to "what provides function". 
- urban design is poor if monocultures are only used},
author = {Cameron, Ross W.F. and Blanu{\v{s}}a, Tijana},
